COPY public.designations (id, name, alias, basics_description, generate_slug, slug, updated_at, created_at) FROM stdin;
1	Sporting Director	sporting-director	A senior leadership position responsible for all trackside and competitive aspects of race operations. The Sporting Director oversees race strategy formulation, driver management during events, pit wall communications, and adherence to sporting regulations. This role serves as the primary interface between the team and Race Control, Stewards, and Series officials. The Sporting Director manages the race engineers, strategists, and sporting coordinators while maintaining direct communication channels with drivers regarding on-track conduct, rule compliance, and competitive positioning throughout race weekends. They interpret sporting regulations, manage protest and appeal procedures, and ensure the team maximizes competitive advantage within the regulatory framework. During race sessions, the Sporting Director operates from the pit wall or command center, making real-time decisions on tire strategy, pit stop timing, driver swaps in endurance racing, and responses to safety car periods or red flag situations. The role requires comprehensive knowledge of series sporting codes, exceptional decision-making under pressure, and diplomatic skills for official interactions	f	sporting-director	2026-04-09 18:32:15.714+05:30	2026-04-09 18:32:15.714+05:30
2	Team Principal	team-principal	description": "The highest-ranking executive role within a motorsport team. The Team Principal holds ultimate responsibility for all aspects of team operations including competitive performance, strategic direction, financial management, personnel decisions, and stakeholder relations. This role serves as the primary public face of the organization during race weekends, media engagements, and official FIA and series proceedings. The Team Principal works in concert with Sporting Directors, Technical Directors, and Commercial Directors to ensure cohesive execution of the team's vision across all departments. In the paddock hierarchy, the Team Principal is the final authority on all matters pertaining to the team's participation in championships, driver selections, and major technical partnerships. They represent the team in all high-level negotiations with series organizers, sponsors, and governing bodies. The role demands exceptional leadership qualities, deep motorsport knowledge, strategic acumen, and the ability to perform under intense public and competitive pressure.	f	team-principal	2026-04-09 18:32:48.67+05:30	2026-04-09 18:32:48.67+05:30
3	Commercial Director	commercial-director	A senior executive role responsible for all revenue generation, partnership management, and commercial strategy within a motorsport organization. The Commercial Director leads sponsorship acquisition and retention, hospitality programs, merchandise operations, licensing agreements, and brand partnership activations. This role manages the commercial team including sponsorship managers, partnership coordinators, hospitality executives, and retail operations staff. The Commercial Director develops and executes the commercial strategy aligned with the team's competitive and brand positioning, identifying target partners whose values and objectives match the organization's profile. They negotiate all commercial agreements from primary title partnerships to technical supplier arrangements, ensuring maximum value extraction and mutually beneficial relationships. The Commercial Director works closely with marketing and communications to activate partner rights, deliver contracted benefits, and measure return on investment. This position requires exceptional business development skills, deep understanding of sponsorship valuation, contract negotiation expertise, and the ability to articulate motorsport's unique value proposition to corporate decision-makers.	f	commercial-director	2026-04-09 18:33:39.735+05:30	2026-04-09 18:33:39.735+05:30
4	Technical Director	technical-director	The senior-most engineering and technical authority within a motorsport organization. The Technical Director oversees all aspects of vehicle design, development, setup, and performance optimization. This role leads the engineering department including chief designers, aerodynamicists, vehicle dynamicists, simulation engineers, and trackside performance engineers. The Technical Director establishes the technical philosophy and development roadmap for current and future race cars, balancing performance targets with regulatory compliance and resource constraints. They are responsible for interpreting technical regulations, managing homologation processes, and representing the team in technical working groups with series organizers and governing bodies. At race events, the Technical Director ensures all cars comply with technical regulations, oversees setup direction, and leads engineering debriefs. The position demands world-class engineering expertise across multiple disciplines including aerodynamics, vehicle dynamics, powertrain, materials science, and data analysis, combined with strong leadership and communication skills to direct large technical teams.	f	technical-director	2026-04-09 18:33:41.376+05:30	2026-04-09 18:33:41.376+05:30
5	Chief Race Engineer	chief-race-engineer	A senior engineering position that leads all trackside engineering operations and race event performance optimization. The Chief Race Engineer manages the race engineering team assigned to each car entry, coordinating setup direction, strategy development, and performance analysis across the team's entries. This role serves as the primary engineering interface with drivers regarding car behavior, handling characteristics, and performance feedback translation into setup changes. During race weekends, the Chief Race Engineer oversees all engineering sessions including practice, qualifying, and race, making high-level decisions on setup philosophy, tire compound selection, and strategic options in consultation with the Sporting Director. They lead post-session engineering debriefs, synthesizing driver feedback, data analysis, and simulation outputs into actionable setup developments. The Chief Race Engineer manages the relationship between factory-based design teams and trackside operations, ensuring effective communication of development needs and performance observations. This position demands extensive experience in race engineering at high levels of motorsport, expert-level data analysis capabilities, deep vehicle dynamics knowledge, and exceptional communication skills for driver interaction.	f	chief-race-engineer	2026-04-09 18:33:47.831+05:30	2026-04-09 18:33:47.831+05:30
6	Performance Engineer	performance-engineer	A specialized engineering role focused on extracting maximum vehicle performance through data analysis, simulation, and setup optimization. The Performance Engineer works alongside the Race Engineer, providing deep analytical support through telemetry analysis, lap time simulation, tire modeling, and competitor performance benchmarking. This role manages the team's simulation tools and models, ensuring correlation between predicted and actual vehicle behavior, and identifying areas for setup improvement or driver technique refinement. Performance Engineers conduct pre-event simulation work to establish baseline setups and strategic options, then validate and refine these models during track sessions using real-time telemetry. They analyze competitor data where available to identify relative strengths and weaknesses, informing race strategy and development priorities. The role requires advanced expertise in vehicle dynamics, data science, programming for analysis automation, and simulation toolchains. Performance Engineers must translate complex analytical findings into clear, actionable recommendations for Race Engineers and drivers, bridging the gap between data science and practical trackside application.	f	performance-engineer	2026-04-09 18:33:54.928+05:30	2026-04-09 18:33:54.928+05:30
7	Head of Communications	head-of-communications	A senior role responsible for all external and internal communications, public relations, and media strategy for a motorsport organization. The Head of Communications manages the team's public image, media relationships, crisis communications, and narrative development across all channels. This role leads the communications team including press officers, social media managers, content creators, and internal communications specialists. The Head of Communications develops and executes comprehensive communications strategies that align with team branding, commercial partnerships, and competitive positioning. They manage all media interactions including press releases, interview coordination, press conference preparation, and journalist relationship cultivation. During race weekends, the Head of Communications oversees the media center operations, manages driver and leadership media availability, and handles sensitive or crisis communications with precision and strategic intent. This position requires exceptional writing and editorial skills, deep understanding of media landscape including traditional and digital channels, crisis management expertise, and the ability to shape compelling narratives that resonate with diverse audiences from hardcore fans to corporate stakeholders	f	head-of-communications	2026-04-09 18:34:40.871+05:30	2026-04-09 18:34:40.871+05:30
8	Driver Coach	driver-coach	A specialized role focused on developing and optimizing driver performance through technique analysis, mental preparation, and personalized guidance. The Driver Coach works directly with drivers to refine racing lines, braking points, corner entry and exit techniques, tire management strategies, and race craft. This role utilizes extensive data analysis including telemetry overlays, video review, and sector time comparisons to identify areas for driver improvement and benchmark against teammates or competitors. Beyond technical driving skills, the Driver Coach addresses mental preparation, focus maintenance, pressure management, and decision-making under race conditions. They develop personalized development plans for each driver, setting measurable performance objectives and tracking progress across sessions and events. The Driver Coach collaborates closely with Race Engineers to ensure setup direction aligns with driver preferences and technique, translating driver feedback into engineering language and vice versa. This position requires extensive high-level driving experience, deep understanding of vehicle dynamics from the cockpit perspective, exceptional communication and teaching abilities, and the psychological insight to motivate and develop elite athletes."	f	driver-coach	2026-04-09 18:35:04.899+05:30	2026-04-09 18:35:04.899+05:30
9	Team Manager	team-manager	A senior operational role responsible for all logistical, administrative, and organizational aspects of a motorsport team's participation in race events and championships. The Team Manager oversees personnel coordination, travel arrangements, equipment logistics, garage operations, and event administration. This role ensures the team operates efficiently and compliantly at all venues, managing accreditation, garage allocation, freight logistics, and hospitality arrangements. The Team Manager serves as the primary operational interface with event organizers, circuit management, and series logistics coordinators, handling all administrative requirements including entry forms, documentation, and compliance submissions. Within the team structure, the Team Manager coordinates schedules for all personnel including drivers, engineers, mechanics, and support staff, ensuring optimal resource allocation and adherence to event timelines. They manage the team's equipment inventory, oversee garage setup and breakdown operations, and maintain operational readiness of all support infrastructure. This position demands exceptional organizational abilities, logistics expertise, personnel management skills, and comprehensive knowledge of paddock operations and series procedures.	f	team-manager	2026-04-09 18:35:33.592+05:30	2026-04-09 18:35:33.592+05:30
\.


