COPY public.skills (id, name, alias, basics_description, details_scale, details_depth, details_rarity, details_complexity, generate_slug, slug, updated_at, created_at) FROM stdin;
4	Tire Management	tire-management	The comprehensive discipline of optimizing tire performance, longevity, and consistency throughout competitive sessions by managing thermal loads, mechanical stress, and wear patterns. Tire management encompasses the full spectrum of driver inputs that affect tire behavior including acceleration aggression, braking intensity, cornering forces, and the timing of these inputs relative to tire temperature states. Elite tire managers understand the complex relationship between surface temperature, core temperature, pressure evolution, and compound behavior, adjusting their driving style in real-time to maintain tires within optimal operating windows. This skill extends beyond individual lap optimization to strategic management across entire stints, balancing short-term pace against long-term degradation. Expert practitioners can identify the precise moment when pushing harder yields diminishing returns due to overheating, and conversely recognize when conservative management is unnecessarily sacrificing performance. The skill incorporates surface management techniques including avoiding graining through proper warm-up procedures, preventing blistering by managing core temperature buildup, and minimizing wear through smooth load application. At the highest levels, tire management becomes a competitive weapon where drivers extract multiple tenths per lap from their tires late in stints while competitors struggle with degraded performance.	Comprehensive	Expert	Rare	Extreme	f	tire-management	2026-04-10 10:42:59.565+05:30	2026-04-09 18:43:15.049+05:30
3	Race Craft	race-craft	The comprehensive art and science of wheel-to-wheel competition encompassing overtaking techniques, defensive positioning, strategic thinking, and psychological warfare in direct combat situations. Race craft transcends pure driving speed, representing the tactical intelligence and situational awareness required to convert raw pace into competitive results. This skill includes the spatial judgment to place a car precisely alongside competitors through braking zones, the timing instinct to execute overtaking maneuvers without contact, and the defensive acumen to protect position without compromising exit speed. Elite race craft practitioners possess an encyclopedic knowledge of their competitors' tendencies, strengths, weaknesses, and psychological profiles, exploiting this intelligence to create and seize opportunities. The skill incorporates energy management in series with hybrid systems or push-to-pass functionality, strategically deploying additional power for maximum competitive effect. Expert race craft requires extraordinary peripheral vision, mirror awareness, and the ability to process multiple dynamic threats simultaneously while maintaining reference points and braking markers. At its highest expression, race craft becomes an intuitive extension of competitive instinct where complex multi-variable scenarios are processed and optimal actions executed at a subconscious level.	Comprehensive	Expert	Unique	Extreme	f	race-craft	2026-04-10 10:43:49.017+05:30	2026-04-09 18:43:10.682+05:30
2	Trail Braking	trail-braking	The sophisticated driving technique of continuing brake application after turn-in, gradually reducing brake pressure as steering angle increases through corner entry. Trail braking manipulates the vehicle's weight distribution to maintain front tire contact patch load during the critical transition from straight-line braking to cornering, effectively combining deceleration and lateral acceleration phases that novices treat as discrete events. This skill fundamentally alters a car's corner entry behavior by keeping the front suspension compressed and the tire contact patch enlarged precisely when steering inputs demand maximum front grip. Expert trail brakers use this technique to induce controlled rotation, helping the rear of the car pivot around the corner while the loaded front tires provide precise directional response. The technique requires extraordinary coordination between brake pedal release rate and steering wheel rotation, with the optimal relationship varying by corner type, vehicle characteristics, tire compound behavior, and driver preference. Mastery enables corner entry speeds that exceed static grip calculations by exploiting the dynamic weight transfer window, effectively expanding the vehicle's performance envelope beyond its nominal mechanical limits.	Narrow	Expert	Rare	Extreme	f	trail-braking	2026-04-10 10:44:02.515+05:30	2026-04-09 18:42:41.018+05:30
6	Wet Weather Driving	wet-weather-driving	The specialized driving discipline required to extract maximum performance in reduced-grip conditions including rain, damp tracks, and variable surface moisture. Wet weather driving fundamentally transforms vehicle dynamics, requiring complete recalibration of all driving inputs and the development of unique techniques that exploit available grip while managing the dramatically reduced performance envelope. Expert wet weather drivers possess extraordinary sensitivity to grip variations across the track surface, identifying wet patches, standing water, rivers, and drying lines through visual, tactile, and vehicle behavior cues. This skill includes the ability to identify and exploit the grippier 'wet line' that often diverges significantly from the traditional dry racing line, running wider entries, later apexes, and avoiding rubbered-in sections that become treacherously slippery when wet. Mastery requires understanding of tire behavior in wet conditions including tread pattern effectiveness at different water depths, temperature management challenges, and the precise moment when conditions justify transition to intermediate or slick tires. Elite wet weather performers can process multiple grip references simultaneously, building a dynamic mental map of track conditions that evolves with every lap as rain intensity changes, standing water shifts, and the racing line slowly dries.	Moderate	Expert	Rare	High	f	wet-weather-driving	2026-04-10 10:41:44.66+05:30	2026-04-09 18:44:29.401+05:30
5	Data Analysis Interpretation	data-analysis-interpretation	The technical skill of extracting actionable performance insights from telemetry data, video analysis, and performance metrics to identify improvement opportunities and optimize driving technique. This skill bridges the gap between raw data streams from vehicle sensors and tangible changes to driving inputs, setup direction, or strategic approach. Proficient practitioners understand the relationships between hundreds of data channels including throttle position, brake pressure, steering angle, lateral and longitudinal acceleration, wheel speeds, damper positions, and aerodynamic load sensors. They can correlate data anomalies with specific track features, driving technique issues, or mechanical behaviors, translating complex multi-channel information into clear cause-and-effect narratives. Expert data interpreters recognize subtle patterns that indicate performance limitations such as understeer entry phase, mid-corner push, exit oversteer, or traction deficits, and can identify whether these originate from driving technique, setup compromise, or vehicle characteristics. The skill includes the ability to overlay telemetry from different drivers or sessions, identifying precise locations and magnitudes of performance differentials. At the highest level, this capability enables drivers to self-diagnose technique flaws, validate setup changes, and continuously refine their performance without requiring external coaching interpretation.	Broad	Advanced	Uncommon	High	f	data-analysis-interpretation	2026-04-10 10:42:23.775+05:30	2026-04-09 18:43:20.648+05:30
1	Threshold Braking	threshold-braking	The advanced driving technique of applying maximum brake pressure at the absolute limit of tire adhesion without triggering wheel lockup or ABS intervention. This skill represents the pinnacle of braking proficiency in motorsport, allowing a driver to extract maximum deceleration from the vehicle by maintaining tire slip at the optimal percentage—typically between five and twelve percent longitudinal slip depending on tire compound and track conditions. Mastery of threshold braking requires exquisite sensitivity to pedal pressure feedback, the ability to modulate force in response to changing grip levels, and the spatial awareness to adjust braking points as fuel load, tire degradation, and track evolution alter the available traction throughout a stint. Expert practitioners can detect the subtle vibrational cues that precede lockup, making micro-adjustments to pedal pressure measured in millimeters of travel and kilograms of force. This skill is foundational to lap time generation, as braking zones represent the greatest opportunity for time gain or loss on any circuit. Drivers who excel at threshold braking consistently out-perform telemetry predictions, carrying more speed deeper into corners while maintaining perfect vehicle stability."	Narrow	Expert	Rare	Extreme	f	threshold-braking	2026-04-10 10:44:32.275+05:30	2026-04-09 18:40:57.931+05:30
\.


